    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are tracker episodes in software development?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Tracker episodes refer to sequential state entities used to monitor user progress through a series of events, content pieces, or stages. They are a common pattern in streaming apps, learning platforms, and task management tools."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do you store watched status for tracker episodes?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Watched status is typically stored in a relational database using a joining table (like user_episodes) that links a user ID to an episode ID, along with metadata such as progress percentage, completion timestamp, and a boolean flag indicating if it is fully watched."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why are tracker episodes important for state management?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "They provide a perfect, isolated use case for learning complex state management. Handling tracker episodes requires dealing with asynchronous updates, optimistic UI rendering, data persistence, and resolving conflicts when users access the app from multiple devices."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I build a tracker episode app without a backend?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, you can build a purely client-side episode tracker using technologies like LocalStorage, IndexedDB, or even simply encoding the state in the URL. However, a backend is required if you want the user's progress to sync across different devices."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best database for tracking episodes?",
